The paper deals with Information Extraction, which is a subfield of Natural Language Processing (NLP) and falls under the Computer Science category. The paper specifically focuses on Definition Extraction (DE), which is a task related to text classification and sequence labeling. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CL (Computation and Language), which deals with NLP and related tasks. 

The paper also employs deep learning architectures and graph convolutional neural networks, which are commonly used in Artificial Intelligence (AI) and Machine Learning (ML) research. Therefore, cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) is also a likely sub-category. 

The paper's focus on improving the quality of representation vectors for DE suggests that it may also fall under cs.LG (Learning), which deals with the theoretical foundations of ML and deep learning. 

The paper's use of semantic consistencies and multi-task learning to improve DE also suggests that it may fall under cs.IR (Information Retrieval), which deals with techniques for retrieving relevant information from large datasets. 

Finally, the paper's use of deep learning architectures and graph convolutional neural networks to predict dependency paths between terms and definitions suggests that it may also fall under cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing), which deals with the development and application of neural networks and evolutionary algorithms.
